---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';

// Campaign landing page for prop-firm / funded futures traders.
// Intentionally noindex: this is a single-purpose conversion LP for a channel test,
// kept separate from the indexed SEO pages (/use-cases/prop-firm-behavioral-risk-control,
// /compare/meridian-vs-prop-firm-lockouts) so it doesn't cannibalize them.
const metadata = {
  title: 'Meridian for Prop & Funded Futures Traders — Lock Out Tilt Before It Breaches',
  ignoreTitleTemplate: true,
  description:
    "You passed the eval. Tilt is what takes it back. Meridian Guard reads the behavior that breaches drawdown limits — revenge entries, oversizing, holding losers — and locks you out at a line you set when calm. Strict Lock means you can't unset it in the moment. NinjaTrader 8 today; standalone Tradovate & Ironbeam in early access.",
  robots: { index: false, follow: true },
};

const objections = [
  {
    q: "I don't want software stopping me from trading.",
    a: "It doesn't trade for you and it doesn't decide your strategy. You set one line — your number — when you're calm. Guard only blocks adding risk past that line. Closing or reducing a position is never blocked. The only thing it takes away is the version of you that wants to double down at the worst possible moment.",
  },
  {
    q: "Won't it interfere with my prop firm's platform?",
    a: "No. Meridian runs as its own local layer on your NinjaTrader 8 or Tradovate connection, independent of the firm's infrastructure. Keep the firm's daily-loss lock as your hard floor — Meridian sits above it as the earlier line, so a session rarely reaches that floor at all.",
  },
  {
    q: "Does it work on evaluation and funded accounts?",
    a: "Yes — any NinjaTrader 8 broker connection, including evaluation and funded accounts on Tradovate and Rithmic. License validation has a 7-day offline grace window for locked-down prop environments. On a Tradovate eval or demo account, the standalone app can additionally write Tradovate's own liquidate-only lock at the broker (funded/live Tradovate, Ironbeam, and NinjaTrader don't expose that API — there enforcement is at the app/connection level).",
  },
  {
    q: "What stops me from just restarting to trade again?",
    a: "A Guard pause and Strict Lock survive an NT8 restart or a crash — they hold for the full window you set. 'Close it and reopen' is not an exit. That's the whole point: the rule has to hold in the exact moment you'd want to break it.",
  },
];
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <section class="px-6 pt-16 pb-14 md:pt-20 md:pb-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.18em] uppercase mb-4" style="color:var(--aw-color-primary);">
        For prop-firm &amp; funded futures traders
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-bold text-zinc-900 leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-6">
        You passed the eval.<br />Don't let tilt take it back.
      </h1>
      <p class="text-[18px] md:text-[20px] text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
        It's almost never the strategy that ends a funded account. It's one session — the revenge entries after a bad
        stop, the size creeping up to make it back, the loser you hold too long — that breaches the drawdown limit before
        you stop yourself. <strong class="text-zinc-900">Meridian Guard reads that behavior live and locks you out at a
        line you set when you're calm.</strong> Strict Lock means you can't unset it when you're not.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <a
          href="/pricing"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-7 py-3.5 rounded-full text-[15px] font-semibold text-white shadow-sm"
          style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"
        >
          Start your 14-day free trial
        </a>
        <a
          href="/guard"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-7 py-3.5 rounded-full text-[15px] font-semibold border border-zinc-300 text-zinc-700 hover:border-zinc-500 transition-colors"
        >
          How Guard enforcement works &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-[12px] text-zinc-500 leading-relaxed">
        Official NinjaTrader Ecosystem Vendor &middot; NinjaTrader 8 today &middot; standalone Tradovate &amp; Ironbeam
        in early access &middot; one license covers every platform
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 py-12 border-t border-zinc-100">
    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-[1.6rem] font-bold text-zinc-900 tracking-tight mb-4">How a funded account actually dies</h2>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-zinc-700 leading-[1.85] mb-4">
        You take a stop you didn't deserve. The next entry comes in faster than your plan allows, a size larger, to get
        it back. It loses too. Now the interval shrinks and the size climbs again — and somewhere in that sequence the
        daily loss limit fires, the account is done, and the strategy that earned it never had anything to do with it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-zinc-700 leading-[1.85]">
        The prop firm's limit is a real backstop, but it's the <em>last</em> line. It can only confirm the damage after
        the trade that did it has already filled. The four trades that got you there were behavior — and behavior shows
        up in your order stream long before the P&amp;L does.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 py-12 border-t border-zinc-100">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-[1.6rem] font-bold text-zinc-900 tracking-tight mb-6">
        A stop your prop firm's limit can't give you
      </h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200 px-6 py-5">
          <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.12em] uppercase text-zinc-400 mb-2">The platform lock</p>
          <p class="text-[15px] text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed">
            Fires on a dollar figure, after the loss is realized. Binary: you're trading, then you're locked. It never
            knows <em>why</em> you're losing — only the number.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-emerald-200 px-6 py-5" style="background:#f0fdf4;">
          <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.12em] uppercase mb-2" style="color:var(--aw-color-primary);">
            Meridian Guard
          </p>
          <p class="text-[15px] text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed">
            Fires on the behavior that drives you to the number — revenge entries, oversizing, holding losers — at a
            threshold you set, before the breach line.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-[17px] text-zinc-700 leading-[1.85] mb-4">
        Set Guard's <strong class="text-zinc-900">Session P&amp;L Below</strong> trigger a little above your evaluation's
        maximum daily loss, and the session ends on your buffer — not on a forced breach. Stack the behavioral triggers
        underneath it and the line moves even earlier:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2.5 mb-2 text-[16px] text-zinc-700">
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-zinc-900">PSI entry block</strong> — new entries blocked when your live stability score drops past a floor you choose, even if no dollar limit is close.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-zinc-900">Consecutive-loss cooldown</strong> — an enforced pause after N losses in a row, regardless of where P&amp;L sits at that moment.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-zinc-900">Escalating response</strong> — Notify, a typed acknowledgment, a full trading pause, or a broker disconnect. Exactly as far as you decide, set when calm.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 py-12 border-t border-zinc-100">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <div class="rounded-3xl border border-emerald-200 px-7 py-8 md:px-10 md:py-10" style="background:#f0fdf4;">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.14em] uppercase mb-3" style="color:var(--aw-color-primary);">
          The part that makes it actually work
        </p>
        <h2 class="text-[1.6rem] md:text-[1.9rem] font-bold text-zinc-900 tracking-tight mb-4">
          Strict Lock: a rule you can't talk yourself out of
        </h2>
        <p class="text-[17px] text-zinc-700 leading-[1.85] mb-5">
          Every self-lockout fails the same way — you bypass it in the one moment it matters. Strict Lock removes the
          escape hatches. Arm it once, when you're calm, and for the full window of any pause it fires:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2.5 text-[16px] text-zinc-700">
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
            <span>No ending the pause early, and the Force Reset button is hidden.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
            <span>Guard's master switch — and Strict Lock itself — can't be turned off until it releases.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
            <span>The rule set is frozen. You can add a stricter rule; you can't loosen or delete one.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
            <span>It survives an NT8 restart or crash, and releases on its own when the window expires.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full shrink-0" style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"></span>
            <span>Closing or reducing a position is always allowed — enforcement only ever blocks new or increasing risk.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 py-12 border-t border-zinc-100">
    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="text-[1.6rem] font-bold text-zinc-900 tracking-tight mb-7">Straight answers</h2>
      <dl class="space-y-7">
        {
          objections.map(({ q, a }) => (
            <div>
              <dt class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 text-[17px] mb-1.5">{q}</dt>
              <dd class="text-zinc-600 text-[16px] leading-[1.8]">{a}</dd>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 py-14 border-t border-zinc-100">
    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto text-center">
      <h2 class="text-[1.7rem] md:text-[2rem] font-bold text-zinc-900 tracking-tight mb-4">
        Protect the account you worked to earn.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed mb-7">
        Set the line once, while you're thinking clearly. Let Guard hold it when you're not.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <a
          href="/pricing"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-7 py-3.5 rounded-full text-[15px] font-semibold text-white shadow-sm"
          style="background:var(--aw-color-primary);"
        >
          Start your 14-day free trial
        </a>
        <a
          href="/use-cases/prop-firm-behavioral-risk-control"
          class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-7 py-3.5 rounded-full text-[15px] font-semibold border border-zinc-300 text-zinc-700 hover:border-zinc-500 transition-colors"
        >
          Read the full breakdown &rarr;
        </a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-[12px] text-zinc-500">14-day free trial &middot; card required &middot; cancel any time before day 14 and you pay nothing</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">
      <p class="text-[12px] text-zinc-400 leading-relaxed border-t border-zinc-100 pt-6">
        Trading involves substantial risk of loss. Meridian is a behavioral monitoring tool and does not provide trading
        signals, financial advice, or profit guarantees. Past performance is not indicative of future results; results
        may vary. NinjaTrader&reg; is a registered trademark of NinjaTrader LLC; Meridian is an independent third-party
        add-on and is not owned by NinjaTrader LLC.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
